1.1.11.4 Updated module: unittest
.................................

The *Note unittest: 187. module was greatly enhanced; many new features
were added.  Most of these features were implemented by Michael Foord,
unless otherwise noted.  The enhanced version of the module is
downloadable separately for use with Python versions 2.4 to 2.6,
packaged as the `unittest2' package, from
<https://pypi.python.org/pypi/unittest2>.

When used from the command line, the module can automatically discover
tests.  It’s not as fancy as py.test(1) or nose(2), but provides a
simple way to run tests kept within a set of package directories.  For
example, the following command will search the `test/' subdirectory for
any importable test files named `test*.py':

    python -m unittest discover -s test

Consult the *Note unittest: 187. module documentation for more details.
(Developed in issue 6001(3).)

The *Note main(): 27b. function supports some other new options:

   * *Note -b: 27c. or `--buffer' will buffer the standard output and
     standard error streams during each test.  If the test passes, any
     resulting output will be discarded; on failure, the buffered
     output will be displayed.

   * *Note -c: 27d. or `--catch' will cause the control-C interrupt to
     be handled more gracefully.  Instead of interrupting the test
     process immediately, the currently running test will be completed
     and then the partial results up to the interruption will be
     reported.  If you’re impatient, a second press of control-C will
     cause an immediate interruption.

     This control-C handler tries to avoid causing problems when the
     code being tested or the tests being run have defined a signal
     handler of their own, by noticing that a signal handler was
     already set and calling it.  If this doesn’t work for you,
     there’s a *Note removeHandler(): 27e. decorator that can be used
     to mark tests that should have the control-C handling disabled.

   * *Note -f: 27f. or `--failfast' makes test execution stop
     immediately when a test fails instead of continuing to execute
     further tests.  (Suggested by Cliff Dyer and implemented by
     Michael Foord; issue 8074(4).)

The progress messages now show ‘x’ for expected failures and
‘u’ for unexpected successes when run in verbose mode.
(Contributed by Benjamin Peterson.)

Test cases can raise the *Note SkipTest: 280. exception to skip a test
(issue 1034053(5)).

The error messages for *Note assertEqual(): 281, *Note assertTrue():
282, and *Note assertFalse(): 283.  failures now provide more
information.  If you set the *Note longMessage: 284. attribute of your
*Note TestCase: 285. classes to true, both the standard error message
and any additional message you provide will be printed for failures.
(Added by Michael Foord; issue 5663(6).)

The *Note assertRaises(): 286. method now returns a context handler
when called without providing a callable object to run.  For example,
you can write this:

    with self.assertRaises(KeyError):
        {}['foo']

(Implemented by Antoine Pitrou; issue 4444(7).)

Module- and class-level setup and teardown fixtures are now supported.
Modules can contain `setUpModule()' and `tearDownModule()' functions.
Classes can have *Note setUpClass(): 287. and *Note tearDownClass():
288. methods that must be defined as class methods (using
`@classmethod' or equivalent).  These functions and methods are invoked
when the test runner switches to a test case in a different module or
class.

The methods *Note addCleanup(): 289. and *Note doCleanups(): 28a. were
added.  *Note addCleanup(): 289. lets you add cleanup functions that
will be called unconditionally (after *Note setUp(): 28b. if *Note
setUp(): 28b. fails, otherwise after *Note tearDown(): 28c.). This
allows for much simpler resource allocation and deallocation during
tests (issue 5679(8)).

A number of new methods were added that provide more specialized tests.
Many of these methods were written by Google engineers for use in
their test suites; Gregory P. Smith, Michael Foord, and GvR worked on
merging them into Python’s version of *Note unittest: 187.

   * *Note assertIsNone(): 28d. and *Note assertIsNotNone(): 28e. take
     one expression and verify that the result is or is not `None'.

   * *Note assertIs(): 28f. and *Note assertIsNot(): 290.  take two
     values and check whether the two values evaluate to the same
     object or not.  (Added by Michael Foord; issue 2578(9).)

   * *Note assertIsInstance(): 291. and *Note assertNotIsInstance():
     292. check whether the resulting object is an instance of a
     particular class, or of one of a tuple of classes.  (Added by
     Georg Brandl; issue 7031(10).)

   * *Note assertGreater(): 293, *Note assertGreaterEqual(): 294, *Note
     assertLess(): 295, and *Note assertLessEqual(): 296. compare two
     quantities.

   * *Note assertMultiLineEqual(): 297. compares two strings, and if
     they’re not equal, displays a helpful comparison that highlights
     the differences in the two strings.  This comparison is now used by
     default when Unicode strings are compared with *Note
     assertEqual(): 281.

   * *Note assertRegexpMatches(): 298. and *Note
     assertNotRegexpMatches(): 299. checks whether the first argument
     is a string matching or not matching the regular expression
     provided as the second argument (issue 8038(11)).

   * *Note assertRaisesRegexp(): 29a. checks whether a particular
     exception is raised, and then also checks that the string
     representation of the exception matches the provided regular
     expression.

   * *Note assertIn(): 29b. and *Note assertNotIn(): 29c.  tests
     whether `first' is or is not in  `second'.

   * *Note assertItemsEqual(): 29d. tests whether two provided sequences
     contain the same elements.

   * *Note assertSetEqual(): 29e. compares whether two sets are equal,
     and only reports the differences between the sets in case of error.

   * Similarly, *Note assertListEqual(): 29f. and *Note
     assertTupleEqual(): 2a0.  compare the specified types and explain
     any differences without necessarily printing their full values;
     these methods are now used by default when comparing lists and
     tuples using *Note assertEqual(): 281.  More generally, *Note
     assertSequenceEqual(): 2a1. compares two sequences and can
     optionally check whether both sequences are of a particular type.

   * *Note assertDictEqual(): 2a2. compares two dictionaries and
     reports the differences; it’s now used by default when you
     compare two dictionaries using *Note assertEqual(): 281.  *Note
     assertDictContainsSubset(): 2a3. checks whether all of the
     key/value pairs in `first' are found in `second'.

   * *Note assertAlmostEqual(): 2a4. and *Note assertNotAlmostEqual():
     2a5. test whether `first' and `second' are approximately equal.
     This method can either round their difference to an
     optionally-specified number of `places' (the default is 7) and
     compare it to zero, or require the difference to be smaller than a
     supplied `delta' value.

   * *Note loadTestsFromName(): 2a6. properly honors the *Note
     suiteClass: 2a7. attribute of the *Note TestLoader: 2a8. (Fixed by
     Mark Roddy; issue 6866(12).)

   * A new hook lets you extend the *Note assertEqual(): 281. method to
     handle new data types.  The *Note addTypeEqualityFunc(): 2a9.
     method takes a type object and a function. The function will be
     used when both of the objects being compared are of the specified
     type.  This function should compare the two objects and raise an
     exception if they don’t match; it’s a good idea for the
     function to provide additional information about why the two
     objects aren’t matching, much as the new sequence comparison
     methods do.

*Note unittest.main(): 27b. now takes an optional `exit' argument.  If
false, *Note main(): 27b. doesn’t call *Note sys.exit(): 2aa, allowing
*Note main(): 27b. to be used from the interactive interpreter.
(Contributed by J. Pablo Fernández; issue 3379(13).)

*Note TestResult: 2ab. has new *Note startTestRun(): 2ac. and *Note
stopTestRun(): 2ad. methods that are called immediately before and
after a test run.  (Contributed by Robert Collins; issue 5728(14).)

With all these changes, the `unittest.py' was becoming awkwardly large,
so the module was turned into a package and the code split into several
files (by Benjamin Peterson).  This doesn’t affect how the module is
imported or used.

See also
........

<http://www.voidspace.org.uk/python/articles/unittest2.shtml>
     Describes the new features, how to use them, and the rationale for
     various design decisions.  (By Michael Foord.)

